This Week's Demos (June 8, 2026)Networking

Public IP Network Attachments  (Recording
<https://drive.google.com/file/d/1SPG1nQxD1IDJIE6ytZgDhbElt2BzmAwp/view>
06:50 - 50:15)

   -

   Public IP allocation was already demonstrated a few weeks ago. This demo
   focused on the next step: attaching allocated IPs to tenant workloads, not
   only to ComputeInstances, and managing them throughout their lifecycle.
   -

   The team presented the updated IP model, including a dedicated
   attachment concept that allows IPs to be associated with different workload
   types such as compute instances, clusters, or bare metal servers. The demo
   covered the main user flow: pool management, IP allocation, attachment,
   connectivity validation, detachment, and cleanup.
   -

   The discussion also covered customer-facing terminology, since “Public
   IP” may be misleading when the IP is not necessarily internet-routable.
   Alternatives such as “External IP,” “Floating IP,” or “Virtual IP” were
   suggested.


   -

   Follow-up actions:
   -

      Align on customer-facing terminology.
      -

      Explore simplified one-shot workflows.
      -

      Public IP backend integration: extend Public IP support across
      additional networking backends, including Netris and Ansible-based VLAN
      networking.

Ansible VLAN Networking (Recording
<https://drive.google.com/file/d/1YrMQ_RbvpHJ8SmvT0ssyxedEts_IWLsH/view?usp=drive_link>
28:24 - 01:05:05)

   -

   Demonstrated a new Ansible-based networking backend that can provide
   tenant network isolation as an alternative to Netris/MOC.
   -

   The solution uses Ansible networking to configure both the switches and
   the router: switch access ports are assigned to tenant-specific VLANs, and
   the router uses a separate namespace per tenant.
   -

   The demo showed how different tenants can be placed on separate VLANs,
   ensuring that workloads from one tenant cannot communicate with another
   tenant.
   -

   Follow-up actions:


   -

   Integrate the networking backend into the Cluster as a Service workflow.
   -

   Explore the BMO(BareMetalOperator) multi-tenancy solution, as they may
   have a similar VLAN-based approach.

Core

Project Management APIs (Recording
<https://drive.google.com/file/d/1YrMQ_RbvpHJ8SmvT0ssyxedEts_IWLsH/view?usp=drive_link>
06:06 - 28:12)

   -

   Demonstrated new project management APIs that provide multi-tenancy
   support in OSAC, where a project acts as a boundary within a tenant,
   similar to an OpenShift namespace.
   -

   The demo showed a tenant admin creating a project through the OSAC CLI,
   verifying it in Keycloak, and confirming that unauthorized users cannot
   access it.
   -

   The model supports nested projects and project-level access control,
   including manager and viewer roles.
   -

   Projects will be used to scope OSAC resources, with a default project
   per tenant. Shared/global resources will reside under a shared tenant
   project.
   -

   Follow-up actions:
   -

      Add support for assigning and removing users from projects.
      -

      Implement resource filtering by project.
      -

      Complete tenant admin APIs for identity provider and role management.
      -

      Enable resources to be assigned to multiple projects.

